    "summary": "The Art of War (c. 500–400 BC), attributed to the military strategist Sun Tzu (Sun Wu), is a Chinese treatise on military strategy and tactics that remains one of the most influential texts on warfare, strategy, and competition in world history — still required reading in military academies and business schools alike.\n\nComposed during the early [[event:1111|Warring States Period]], the Art of War consists of thirteen short chapters covering topics including strategy, tactical positioning, use of intelligence, management of troops, and the importance of deception. Its central insight — that the supreme achievement in warfare is to defeat the enemy without fighting — reflects a sophisticated understanding of strategy as manipulation of conditions rather than simple force. The text emphasizes flexibility, intelligence gathering, and exploiting enemy weaknesses over brute strength. Whether Sun Tzu was a historical individual or a compilation of multiple thinkers is debated, but the text's practical wisdom proved enduring: it influenced every major Chinese military tradition, was translated into Japanese (influencing samurai culture), and in modern times has been applied to business strategy, sports coaching, and political campaigning worldwide.",
